APPENDIX A — OPERATIONAL PRIMITIVES AND ONTOLOGICAL PRIMITIVES
------------------------------------------------------------

Purpose
------------------------------------------------------------

This appendix clarifies the relationship between operational
primitives and ontological primitives within theoretical
framework construction.

The distinction is important for understanding how deeper
explanatory layers may be discovered during theory development.


1. Definitions
------------------------------------------------------------

Operational Primitive

Operational primitives are the minimal elements required
for a theory to function at the level of mechanism or
process.

They describe how a system operates in practice.

Operational primitives typically appear in the early stages
of theory development because they correspond to observable
or modelled components of a system.

Examples in coordination systems may include:

• contribution events
• observation of behaviour
• interpretation mechanisms
• allocation mechanisms


Ontological Primitive

Ontological primitives represent deeper conditions that
must exist for the operational primitives themselves to
be meaningful or coherent.

These primitives describe the fundamental structure of
the system's existence rather than its operational
mechanisms.

They answer the question:

"What must be true for the operational mechanisms to exist
at all?"


2. Relationship Between the Two
------------------------------------------------------------

Operational primitives can reveal deeper ontological
primitives when their functional requirements are examined.

If an operational mechanism cannot function without a
particular underlying condition, that condition may
represent a deeper primitive layer of the theory.

The discovery process may therefore proceed as follows:

Operational Primitives
↓
Dependency Analysis
↓
Underlying Condition
↓
Ontological Primitive


3. Example from the Trust Framework
------------------------------------------------------------

Initial operational primitives identified in the Trust
Framework include:

Contribution
Observation
Trust interpretation
Credibility
Credit


Analysis of these mechanisms revealed a deeper requirement.

Trust mechanisms depend on the expectation that interaction
between agents will persist across time.

Without the possibility of continued interaction:

• contributions lose strategic meaning
• observations cannot accumulate
• trust signals become irrelevant


This analysis reveals a deeper primitive condition:

Continuation.


The conceptual hierarchy therefore becomes:

Continuation
↓
Coexistence systems
↓
Coordination mechanisms
↓
Trust formation
↓
Credibility
↓
Credit


4. Methodological Implication
------------------------------------------------------------

Operational primitives within a theoretical framework can
function as probes that expose deeper ontological conditions.

By analysing what must exist for operational mechanisms
to function coherently, researchers may identify more
fundamental primitives underlying the system.

This process corresponds to the methodological pattern
described in this work as:

Vertical Primitive Discovery.


5. Scope and Limitation
------------------------------------------------------------

Operational primitives do not necessarily determine a
unique ontological primitive.

Multiple deeper explanations may sometimes exist.

However, when a single underlying condition consistently
explains the functional requirements of multiple operational
mechanisms, that condition may reasonably be considered a
candidate ontological primitive.


